This paper deals with predicting user connectivity patterns and evaluating the quality of these predictors on various large traces from instant messaging and file sharing applications. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses how availability prediction can be applied to enhance the behavior of peer-to-peer applications, which could also place it in the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category. The use of large traces and data analysis could also suggest the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with predicting user behavior, which could place it in the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-category. The discussion of scarcity of resources and the need for proactive measures could also suggest the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category.
